subSubSection.paragraph:
Song
. Male calling song is a prolonged echeme-sequence lasting about 15–30 s. The song begins quietly and gradually reaches maximum intensity in the first third or half of its duration (
Figs. 61–63
). Typically, each echeme consists of an abrupt “click” followed by two syllables (
Figs. 64–71
). Echeme repetition period gradually decreases towards the middle of a song and more abruptly increases in last ca. 10 echemes (
Tishechkin & Bukhvalova, 2009b, fig. 84
). In males from 
Kyrgyzstan
echeme repetition period in the middle of a song averages 180–240 ms (
Figs. 64–67
). In the nominotypical subspecies, there are few if any gaps in syllables (
Figs. 64–71
), whereas in 

Ch. apricarius major

typically, several gaps present in each syllable (
Figs. 72–74
).
